Data Preparation

Load Data

Load the data imported, processed and saved from “data wrangle change score centroid and map data.R”.

load("processed_data v4.RData")

Prepare Data

Keep distinct records within each time point only because keeping all pairwise records will inflate the number of observations in time 1 and 2.

data_long <- distinct(merged_data_record_all_long, tribe, time, FIPS, .keep_all = TRUE)

Create data.frame to include only tribes with time 1 and 2 data.

data_t1and2_long <- filter(data_long, tribe %in% tribes_time1and2_lst$tribe)

Convert time and tribe to factor for statistical modeling

data_long <- data_long %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(tribe = factor(tribe),
         time = factor(time))

data_t1and2_long <- data_t1and2_long %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(tribe = factor(tribe),
         time = factor(time))

Check Data

First, confirm the data is correct, each tribe should have 2 summarized records in total, one for time 1 and one for time 2, so the resulted data.frame should has 0 row.

t1and2_lst <- group_by(data_t1and2_long, tribe, time) %>% 
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(tribe) %>%
  count() %>%
  filter(n < 2)

nrow(t1and2_lst)
## [1] 0

Exploratory Analyses

All Tribes, including those with time 1 or time 2 data only

Plot Property Damage by Time

  • The distribution of property damage in time 1 and time 2 is skewed to the right and is zero-inflated with notable outliers.
  • The distirbution of property damage is in general higher in time 2 compared to time 1.

Look at those with property damage only and 90th percentile cutoff

  • The distirbution of property damage is in general higher in time 2 compared to time 1 for tribes in counties with property damage only.
data_long_shel_prop_only <- filter(data_long, shel_prop > 0)

ggplot(data_long_shel_prop_only, aes(shel_prop, fill = time)) +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(time), scales = "free") +
  geom_histogram(position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlim(0, quantile(data_long_shel_prop_only$shel_prop, c(.90), na.rm = TRUE))  

ggplot(data_long_shel_prop_only, aes(time, shel_prop, colour = time)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_quasirandom(alpha = 1/10, varwidth = TRUE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylim(0, quantile(data_long_shel_prop_only$shel_prop, c(.90), na.rm = TRUE))

Plot relationship between Time 1 and Time 2 Property Damage at tribe level

  • Compute the mean and median values of each tribe at time 1 and time 2. Look at the median as well as the mean because the median is a robust measure of central tendency and extreme-value resistent while the mean is heavily influenced by outliers.

Relationship between Time 1 and Time 2 Property Damage

  • We found a large positive linear relationships between time 1 and time 2 property damage for mean (r = 0.758) and median (r = 0.5784)

Relationship between Time 1 and Time 2 Property Damage per Capita

  • We found a medium positive linear relationship between time 1 and time 2 property damage per capita for mean (r = 0.3758) and median (r = 0.4895)

Test for Significant Difference

(1) Test for significant difference at the aggregate level

  • We applied three statistical models - Linear Mixed Model, Repeated Measure ANOVA, and Zero-inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model - to examine statistical significant difference between Time 1 and Time 2 property damage and property damage per capita scores.
  • The models, as applicable, are run using all records from all tribes and tribes with both time 1 and 2 data.
  • The model interpretation is based on the Zero-inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model, as this is the test most appropraite for the outcome. The Linear Mixed Model and Repeated Measure ANOVA results are shown for reference purposes.

Use all records

Filter out NA outcomes

model_data_long <- filter(data_long, !is.na(shel_prop))
model_data_t1and2_long <- filter(data_t1and2_long, !is.na(shel_prop))

Linear Mixed Model

  • Linear mixed model is a parametric test for comparing data when one or more of the independent variables should be model as a random effect because of variations by that variable.
# Linear Mixed Model raw
lme_model <- nlme::lme(shel_prop ~ time, data = model_data_long, random = ~1|tribe)

Repeated Measure ANOVA

  • See Analysis below: Repeated Measure ANOVA can only be run with tribes with both time 1 and time 2 data.

Zero-Inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model

  • Zero-inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model is a parametric test for comparing continous metrics with excessive zeros. Unlike t-test or ANOVA, this test is appropriate for data that has a non-normally distribute positive scores with a large amount of zero score, such as the outcome property damage and property damage per capita. It is a two-part models. The first part evalutes whether the outcome is zero or non-zero, the second part models the positive distribution of the non-zero scores. Different predictors can be entered to predict the outcomes in these two-parts.
  • Time is entered as a predictor in both the zero-inflated and positive scores part of the modeling.
# Zero-Inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model! raw
zcpglm_model <- zcpglm(shel_prop ~ time || time, link = "log", data = model_data_long, optimizer = "nlminb")

zcpglm_model_summary <- summary(zcpglm_model)
## 
## Call:
## zcpglm(formula = shel_prop ~ time || time, link = "log", data = model_data_long, 
##     optimizer = "nlminb")
## 
## Zero-inflation model coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value            Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -4.9589     0.1226 -40.449 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## timetime 2   -0.4864     0.5914  -0.822               0.411    
## 
## Compound Poisson model coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value            Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) 12.81192    0.01362  940.69 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## timetime 2   0.53445    0.05214   10.25 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Estimated dispersion parameter: 2.0122
## Estimated index parameter: 1.99
model_para <- coef(zcpglm_model_summary)

mean_t1 <- round(mean(filter(data_long, time == "time 1")$shel_prop, na.rm = T), 3)
mean_t2 <- round(mean(filter(data_long, time == "time 2")$shel_prop, na.rm = T), 3)
sd_t1 <- round(sd(filter(data_long, time == "time 1")$shel_prop, na.rm = T), 3)
sd_t2 <- round(sd(filter(data_long, time == "time 2")$shel_prop, na.rm = T), 3)

pvalue <- round(model_para$tweedie[2,4], 3)
zvalue <- round(model_para$tweedie[2,3], 3)
parameter <- NA

Interpretation

  • At the aggregate level, the difference in property damage between time 1 (M = 364005.496, SD = 1104444.75) and time 2 (M = 622858.081, SD = 1898970.882) was statistically signficant (z = 10.25, p < .001).

  • Zero-inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model is a parametric test for comparing continous metrics with excessive zeros. Unlike t-test or ANOVA, this test is appropriate for data that has a non-normally distribute positive scores with a large amount of zero score, such as the outcome property damage and property damage per capita.   • At the aggregate level for tribes with migration, the difference in property damage area between time 1 (M = 342913.84, SD = 980768.632) and time 2 (M = 606245.124, SD = 1851737.472) was statistically signficant (z = 10.561, p < .001).

(2) Test for significant difference at tribe level

tribe_with_dif <- filter(merged_data_tribe, avg_shel_prop_change_score > 0) %>% group_by(tribe) %>% count()

no_test <- nrow(tribe_with_dif)

This can only be tested with the 184 tribes where migrations occured. Furthermore, only tribes where property damage have changed between time points and with more than one data point at each time point can their differences be tested for statistical significance. This reduce the number of tribes from 184 to 77.

Run Zero-Inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model in Batch

  • Run Zero-Inflated Compound Poisson Generalized Linear Model in batch using group_by and do at the tribe level.
  • Include a try call to catch error.
  • Format the results into a data.frame.
  • Replace NA estimate with all NA for that comparison.
model <- group_by(model_data_t1and2_long, tribe) %>%
do(tryCatch(
  {as.data.frame((coef(summary(zcpglm(shel_prop ~ time || time, link = "log", data = ., optimizer = "nlminb"))))$tweedie)},
  error = function(e) {data.frame(Estimate = NA)}
)) # keep only tweedie time component

model <- group_by(model, tribe) %>% 
  filter(row_number() %% 2 == 0) %>%
  rename(p.value = `Pr(>|z|)`)
model_pc <- group_by(model_data_t1and2_long, tribe) %>%
do(tryCatch(
  {as.data.frame((coef(summary(zcpglm(shel_prop_pc ~ time || time, link = "log", data = ., optimizer = "nlminb"))))$tweedie)},
  error = function(e) {data.frame(Estimate = NA)}
)) # keep only tweedie time component

model_pc <- group_by(model_pc, tribe) %>% 
  filter(row_number() %% 2 == 0) %>%
  rename(p.value = `Pr(>|z|)`)

Calculate number of test based only on tribes where there is non-zero difference and sufficient data point in property damage between time 1 and 2.

no_test <- nrow(filter(model, !is.na(p.value)))
  • Create sig column to flag statistical significance results.
  • p-value cutoff is adjusted to control for Type I error due to multiple comparisons using Bonferroni correction (p value threshold = .05 / number of tests or 167), adjusted p-value threshold = 0.002994.
model <- model %>%
  mutate(sig = ifelse(p.value < .05 / no_test, "yes", "no"))

model_pc <- model_pc %>%
  mutate(sig = ifelse(p.value < .05 / no_test, "yes", "no"))
  • Add damage properties, damage properties per capita, distance, and no of unique FIPS to help with interpretation
  • Rename some variables for prettier column headers
results_df <- inner_join(model, merged_data_tribe, by = "tribe") %>%
  mutate(`Avg Diff Damage Property` = avg_shel_prop_t2 - avg_shel_prop_t1,
         `Avg Diff Damage Property per Capita` = avg_shel_prop_pc_t2 - avg_shel_prop_pc_t1) %>%
  dplyr::select(tribe, sig, p.value, `Avg Diff Damage Property`, avg_shel_prop_t1, avg_shel_prop_t2, `Avg Diff Damage Property per Capita`, avg_shel_prop_pc_t1, avg_shel_prop_pc_t2, n_unique_FIPS_t1, n_unique_FIPS_t2, mid_dist) %>%
  arrange(p.value) %>%
  rename(
    `Avg Damage Property T1` = avg_shel_prop_t1,
    `Avg Damage Property T2` = avg_shel_prop_t2,
    `Avg Damage Property per Capita T1` = avg_shel_prop_pc_t1,
    `Avg Damage Property per Capita T2` = avg_shel_prop_pc_t2,
    `Unique FIPS T1` = n_unique_FIPS_t1,
    `Unique FIPS T2` = n_unique_FIPS_t2,
    `Mid Distance` = mid_dist)

Interpretation

  • The mean property damage comparisons for 4 tribes (Pamunkey, Chippewa, Mohican, Hopi) achieve statistical significance when the Bonferroni correction is used.
  • The mean property damage per capita comparisons for 1 tribes (Pawnee) achieve statistical significance when the Bonferroni correction is used.
  • The tests have low statistical power to detect differences given the number of observations at time 2 is much smaller than time 1.
  • If Bonferroni correction is not used, property damage was significantly differ between time 1 and 2 for 19 tribes :(Pamunkey, Chippewa, Mohican, Hopi, Washoe, Omaha, Blackfeet, Yahooskin, Chickasaw, Klamath, Colorado River, Hupa, Me-Wuk, Absentee-Shawnee, Samish, Puyallup, Quechan, Nez Perce, Sioux).
  • If Bonferroni correction is not used, property damage per capita was significantly differ between time 1 and 2 for 24 tribes :(Chippewa, Mohican, Omaha, Blackfeet, Yahooskin, Klamath, Hupa, Samish, Puyallup, Quechan, Pawnee, Duwamish, Catawba, Hidatsa, Mandan, Caddo, S’Klallam, Cowlitz, Apache, Miccosukee, Arikara, Nipmuc, Comanche, Kiowa).
  • Results with NA p values are from tribes where there isn’t sufficient data points in both time point to perform the planned statistical tests.

Overall Interpretation

  • Overall, statistically significant difference were found at the aggregate level when data for all tribes and tribes with migrations were analyzed on the outcome property damage scores and property damage per capita.

  • At the tribe level, when correction for multiple comparisons was made, property damage for 4 tribes were found to be statistically differ between time 1 and time 2.

  • At the tribe level, when correction for multiple comparisons was made, property damage per capita for 1 tribes were found to be statistically differ between time 1 and time 2.

  • The lack of significant differences at the tribe level could be attributed to the low statistical power arises from the small number of observations at time 2. In some cases, there is only 1 data point in time 2 or time 1.
